# Control 4 — Data Integrity: Tamper-Proof Storage (WORM/Read-Only)
Recordings are initially written to GCP Filestore as transitional storage during the active recording session. Once the recording is finalized it is moved to Google Cloud Storage buckets for long term archival where it resides for the duration of the retention period.

The GCP buckets are configured as dual-region, meaning data is automatically replicated across two geographic regions providing both redundancy and resilience against localized infrastructure events. Soft delete protection is enabled on the buckets which means that even if a delete operation were attempted the object is retained for a defined recovery window rather than being permanently removed immediately. 

Files are encrypted and cannot be modified in place. Once written as GCP Cloud Storage does not allow overwriting an existing object without an explicit versioned write, preserving the integrity of the original recording file.
Access to the buckets is governed entirely through GCP IAM policies. Only cloud administrators hold the permissions necessary to interact with the buckets at an administrative level and that access is logged through GCP Cloud Audit Logs providing a full trail of who accessed or acted on the storage environment and when.

