# Control 9 — Audit Logging: User Activity Logging
All user actions within the recording portal are logged and forwarded to Splunk Cloud where they are available for review and analysis. This covers the full spectrum of user activity including login, playback, download and configuration changes, with each event capturing the relevant identifying information such as user ID, timestamp and the action performed.
In addition to the existing Splunk logging pipeline, there is an ongoing effort to integrate audit event logs with the SecOps team, which will further strengthen visibility and ensure that user activity within the recording environment is factored into the organization's broader security monitoring posture. This integration is currently in progress and we will provide an update on timeline as it becomes available.
As evidence for this control we can provide a sample extract from Splunk showing user activity log events across the different action types along with the field structure confirming user ID and timestamp are consistently captured.

# Control 10 — Audit Logging: Immutable Log Protection
Audit logs in this environment are protected at two levels. Infrastructure logs generated within GCP are routed to log sinks where they are retained and access to those sinks is governed through GCP IAM policies, ensuring that deletion or modification is restricted to only those with the appropriate permissions.
At the application level, logs flowing into Splunk Cloud are inherently protected from modification. As demonstrated during the walkthrough with the audit team, there is no mechanism within Splunk Cloud that allows any user to edit or alter an indexed log event once it has been written. This is a platform level constraint rather than a configuration choice. Furthermore, deletion of any object or index within Splunk Cloud is not something that can be performed unilaterally by internal Splunk administrators. Any such action requires a formal support ticket to be raised with Splunk directly, introducing an external checkpoint that adds an additional layer of protection against unauthorized or accidental log deletion.
As evidence for this control we can provide the GCP log sink configuration along with IAM policy documentation showing access restrictions, and Splunk Cloud configuration details confirming the platform level immutability of indexed events.

# Control 11 — Monitoring: Periodic Log Review
Monitoring and periodic log review for the recording environment falls within the remit of the SecOps team. As audit event logs are being integrated with SecOps as part of the ongoing effort referenced in Control 9, the SecOps team is best positioned to speak to how monitoring is handled, what tooling and processes are in place for anomaly detection, and how suspicious activity is escalated and resolved. We would recommend the audit team engage SecOps directly for evidence and walkthrough of this control.

# Control #12 - Configuration Management
All changes are tracked in Jira Connect Platform Change Management (CPCM) project, including the reason for change, implementation details, testing/validation steps, approvals, and deployment notes. 

Significant or higher-risk changes, such as arch design changes that could impact severy impact production are reviewed through the regular CAB/change management process before implementation.

After deployment, the team validates the change using application checks, Splunk Clud logs, and sample call/recording verification to confirm recording behavior remains operating as expected.

# Control #13 - 
End user access to the call recording application is managed through the Connect Portal. 
The recording application relies on the roles and entitlements passed from the Connect Portal to determine what functions a user can perform, such as search, playback or download where applicable. 

Access is intended to follow least-privilege principles based on the user’s approved role.
Documentation and evidence for the access control workflow, role definitions, approval process, and user-role mapping should be provided by the Connect Portal Team or the Oprtations team who manages the Connect Portal Access. 

